"CS268 Lab Experiment-3 centers on the design and Verilog implementation of Booth's multiplier, an algorithm specifically valued for its efficiency in multiplying signed 2's complement integers by reducing partial products and thus enhancing processing speed. The practical core of the experiment involves analyzing a provided Verilog implementation of the Booth multiplier, which is structured into distinct datapath and control path modules. Students are tasked with understanding the code's operational flow, identifying errors within specific buggy modules or submodules, and then meticulously explaining and correcting these identified bugs to achieve a functional design."